            "role": "assistant",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "I can explain what *sales records* typically are and how they’re used, but I can’t access any actual sales records (or even a schema/field list) from the data available to me in this environment—what I can access here is limited to weather-event data, not sales data【6:0†source】.\n\n## What “sales records” usually mean\nA sales record is a row/entry representing a sales-related business event. Depending on the system, it might be:\n- **An order header** (one per customer order)\n- **Order line items** (one per product/service on the order)\n- **An invoice** (billing document)\n- **A payment/receipt** (money collected)\n- **A return/refund** (reversal/adjustment)\n\n## Common fields you’ll see\nTypical columns (vary by company/system):\n- **Identifiers:** order_id, invoice_id, transaction_id, line_id  \n- **Dates:** order_date, ship_date, invoice_date, payment_date  \n- **Customer:** customer_id, customer_name, segment, geography  \n- **Product:** sku/product_id, description, category, quantity  \n- **Money:** unit_price, discount, tax, shipping, total_amount, currency  \n- **Sales/channel:** salesperson_id, store_id, channel (online/retail/partner)  \n- **Status:** order_status (open/shipped/canceled), payment_status, return_flag  \n- **Audit fields:** created_at, updated_at, source_system\n\n## What sales records are used for\n- **Revenue reporting:** sales by day/week/month, by product, by region\n- **Performance:** salesperson/store/channel comparisons\n- **Customer analytics:** repeat purchase rate, churn, cohort behavior\n- **Operations:** fulfillment time, backorders, returns rate\n- **Finance controls:** reconciliation, tax reporting, fraud detection\n\n## If you want *your* sales records analyzed\nTell me where your sales data lives (e.g., table name, dataset, report, or a CSV you can paste/upload) and what you want to learn (e.g., “total sales last quarter,” “top products,” “returns rate”). I can then help structure queries/metrics—right now I can’t directly retrieve sales records from the available sources here【6:0†source】.",
